Group 1¶

explain why we need to remove certain columns and replace certain values¶

This dataset has missing or unkown data so we use the na_values function to represented these datapoints as NaN values in the DataFrame. later in the code, we are using pokemon_tidy.fillna(0) function to fill NaN values as 0, so we could have all the numeric values in a column to proceed with our analysis and data visualization process. We also remove a lot of columns that either dont fit in with the tidy principles or have mostly unknown values

describe how else you could clean up or enhance the appearance of the graph¶

below is the modificated graph where i showed only top 5 types of pokemons and completely removed the other kinds. I also removed the gridlines, changed the bacjground to white and moved the title to the center . If i were to explore this graph further, i would play arounf with the grouping of elements, as well as the size of dots

In [163]:
# Filtering the data to include only the top 5 stats in the plot

# calculating the total catch for each type by using a groupby function
type_catch_totals = pokemon_tidy.groupby('Type I')['Catch'].sum().reset_index()

# Step 2: Sort types based on total catch and select top 5
top_5_types = type_catch_totals.nlargest(5, 'Catch')['Type I']

# Step 3: Filter data to include only the top 5 types
filtered_data = pokemon_tidy[pokemon_tidy['Type I'].isin(top_5_types)]

# Create the scatter plot
fig = px.scatter(filtered_data, x='Catch', y='Total',
                 color='Type I', size='Catch',
                 title='Top 5 Pokemon Types by Catch Rate and Stat Totals',
                 width=1000, height=750,
                 hover_name='Pokemon',
                 color_discrete_map={'Grass': 'lightgreen',
                                     'Electric': 'gold',
                                     'Water': 'aqua',
                                     'Bug': 'forestgreen',
                                     'Normal': 'dodgerblue'})

# Removing the gridlines and setting the backgroung color to white 
fig.update_layout(
    xaxis=dict(showgrid=False),
    yaxis=dict(showgrid=False),
    plot_bgcolor='white',
    title_x=0.5)

fig.show()

           labels = wq['Site_Id'].unique())

     violin.set_facecolor(color)

fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2)

violins = axs[0,0].violinplot(wq['Water Depth (m)'].groupby(wq['Site_Id']).apply(list), showmeans = False, showmedians = True)
axs[0,0].set_xticks(ticks = range(1, 6),\
           labels = wq['Site_Id'].unique())

for color, violin in zip(colors, violins['bodies']):

axs[0,0].set_ylabel('Water Depth ')

provide a short discussion of the box plot graph you created in step 9 (e.g. how salary distributions are affected by factors of job categories¶

In the box plot created, we are exploring the distribution of salaries across different job categories. Each box represents a specific job category, and the y-axis represents the salary in USD. The boxes represent the IQR for each job category, showing the middle 50% of salaries. The wider box basically means the greater the variability in salaries within that category. We can see that dta architecture and modeling has the biggest range amont others. However, data science and research category has the highest salaries overall. One thing we can say that the highest sallries in this boxplot are mostly outliers, because they are extending from the boxes.
